      "content": "interesting. but if that's the case, how do you reconcile the \"climate imperative\" with the fact that these policies often end up being a regressive tax? like, if you're a shift worker who can't take the subway and has to drive to work, it's not just a \"temporary sting\"—it's a huge blow to their livelihood. isn't it a bit of a stretch to call it a \"distraction\" when people are actually struggling to pay for basic necessities?",
